    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-11-06T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-11-06T06:00:00-05:00" n="1368"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">774.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/11–654:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1368<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            type="from">Caffery</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1368fn1">Repeated to London as telegram 134 and unnumbered
                        to Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv, and the Arab capitals.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-11-06T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 6, 1954—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>620. Atmosphere of exchange of notes re economic aid was almost gala. it is plain
                    Egyptians are very pleased and plan to stress aid as evidence US confidence
                    Egypt’s future.</p>
                <p>I saw <persName corresp="#p_FBM1">Fawzi</persName> privately afterwards. He again
                    reiterated his thanks to all those concerned in Washington and Cairo; he said
                        <gloss target="#t_GOE1">GOE</gloss> fully appreciate the many problems which
                    had to be surmounted in connection with economic aid. <persName
                        corresp="#p_FBM1">Fawzi</persName> went on to say that a committee headed by
                    Finance Minister Kaissuny had been established to implement agreement. He
                    thought there would be no foot dragging.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FBM1">Fawzi</persName> also told me that he had great
                    hopes for increased collaboration between private American and Egyptian firms.
                    He mentioned minerals as being field in which there are great opportunities for
                    American and Egyptian businessmen to work together. He said, “for our part we
                    will give every facility”.<note n="2" xml:id="d1368fn2">According to telegram
                        619 from Cairo, Nov. 6, not printed, the amount of economic development
                        assistance extended by the United States to Egypt totaled $40 million.
                        (774.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/11–654) For the text of this
                        economic development agreement, which was signed and thereby brought into
                        force on Nov. 6, see TIAS No. 3156, 5 <gloss target="#t_UST1">UST</gloss>
                        (pt. 3) 2985.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
